h3. Summary:
Update {{table-content-view.js}}:

From:
{code}
this.$el.find('> tbody > tr').each(function(indexRow, elRow) {...
{code}

To:
{code}
this.$el.find('> tbody > tr:visible').each(function(indexRow, elRow) {...
{code}

h3. Background:
{quote}
There is a capability to create Jira issues from the table with data. We are developing Table Filter and Charts app and want to allow our customers to filter the list of issues and create issues in Jira on the basis of the filtered dataset. Unfortunately now, the whole set of data is used. So we cannot limit visibility of issues to Confluence.
{quote}

h3. Problem Definition

It’s useful for administrators to know the Java version that comes bundled with a particular Confluence installer before starting the installation.
 This is important for companies that adhere to specific versions of Java or need to upgrade it for security compliances.
  
h3. Suggested Solution

It would be useful to add the version of Java bundled with the Confluence installer in their respective release notes.
  
h3. Workaround

An alternative way to find the Java version on a particular Confluence installation is by checking the installation directory:
{panel}
(i) We have to first run the installer to create an installation_directory and home_directory. This does not require going through the setup wizard for Confluence.
{panel}
*Linux/Unix*
{code:java}
# cd {{<installation_directory>}}/jre/bin
 
# ./java -version
{code}
*Windows*
{code:java}
# cd {{<installation_directory>}}\jre\bin
 
# java -version
{code}

h3. Problem Definition
Confluence includes playful text when setting restrictions that states, "Working on something top secret?"

 !topsecret.png|thumbnail! 

For government agencies and other customers that use 'Top Secret' and other forms of clearance, this can lead to confusion (especially if they switch between secure and non-secure networks). 

h3. Suggested Solution
Replace "Working on something top secret?" with different text 

h3. Workaround 
* The text can be hidden by adding the following to the global stylesheet:
{code:borderStyle=solid}
.page-restrictions-dialog-empty-placeholder > h6 {
    display: none !important;
}
{code}
